00:16:07.387 --> 00:16:11.197
So, Carroll decided to prepare the work for publication.

00:16:12.067 --> 00:16:16.117
He added some new stories and characters such as the Mad

00:16:16.127 --> 00:16:20.007
Hatter’s tea party and Alice’s meeting with the Cheshire Cat.

00:16:20.817 --> 00:16:27.017
He also began to think of a new title, with possibilities being Alice Among the Fairies

00:16:27.107 --> 00:16:33.727
or Alice’s Golden Hour but he finally settled on Alice’s Adventures in Wonderland.

00:16:34.967 --> 00:16:40.247
For the book, he also enlisted a man called John Tenniel, a cartoonist,

00:16:40.247 --> 00:16:44.677
or illustrator, from the comedy magazine Punch and one who was

00:16:44.677 --> 00:16:48.437
famous for his animal illustrations in the book Aesop’s Fables.

00:16:49.877 --> 00:16:54.847
By November 1865 the book was published and it did not

00:16:54.877 --> 00:16:58.797
take long for the initial print of 5000 copies to sell out.

00:16:59.967 --> 00:17:04.857
Among the earliest fans of the book were Oscar Wilde and even Queen Victoria.

00:17:05.857 --> 00:17:09.607
And the book’s popularity only grew after its sequel,

00:17:09.907 --> 00:17:13.561
Through the Looking Glass, was published In 1871

00:17:14.807 --> 00:17:21.027
And although Carroll was hesitant about growing famous, and despite the fact that he used a pen

00:17:21.027 --> 00:17:28.147
name, a pseudonym, by the time of his sudden death in 1898 he had become something of a celebrity.

00:17:29.077 --> 00:17:31.607
So what made the books so popular?

00:17:32.357 --> 00:17:38.397
Well, this format of a magical children’s world might seem obvious to us now,

00:17:38.597 --> 00:17:43.717
but back in the late 19th century it was like nothing people had seen before.

00:17:44.837 --> 00:17:51.897
Firstly, Alice was the first children’s novel with a strong and confident female protagonist.

00:17:52.767 --> 00:17:56.687
Clearly, for girls who simply hadn’t ever read stories about

00:17:56.687 --> 00:18:00.747
strong and independent girls before, it must have been wonderful.

00:18:01.977 --> 00:18:06.717
Secondly, the book was hugely innovative through its nonsense, through the

00:18:06.717 --> 00:18:10.827
fact that it didn’t make a huge amount of sense, and that was the beauty of it.

00:18:12.027 --> 00:18:15.737
Traditionally, Victorian children’s books had always been

00:18:15.947 --> 00:18:20.007
dogged with some sort of moral lesson for children to learn.

00:18:20.427 --> 00:18:24.637
Books were viewed as a way for children to be taught how to behave.

00:18:25.717 --> 00:18:31.907
Carroll’s book, however, was written purely to entertain and delight his young audience.

00:18:32.667 --> 00:18:38.687
For the first time, children were being encouraged to simply let their imagination run wild.

00:18:39.767 --> 00:18:45.657
And this has been a recipe for success for centuries afterwards, with Alice in Wonderland

00:18:45.797 --> 00:18:51.917
remaining in print since 1865 and selling at least 100 million copies worldwide.

00:18:53.097 --> 00:18:59.467
If you read it as a child, or if you’ve seen the movie adaptation, you can probably understand why.

00:19:00.915 --> 00:19:07.097
But while the success of Alice has stood the test of time, Carroll’s own reputation has

00:19:07.097 --> 00:19:13.157
not, as debates around his relationship with children have cast a shadow over his career.

00:19:13.997 --> 00:19:17.397
Not only did he spend large amounts of time with young

00:19:17.397 --> 00:19:20.587
children, he took a lot of pictures of the young girls.

00:19:21.517 --> 00:19:25.557
And by modern standards at least, they are quite shocking.

00:19:26.347 --> 00:19:30.437
